				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">By buffering he's referring to either <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_buffering" class="postlink">double buffering or triple buffering</a>.<br /><br />Please note that people who say these techniques solve screen tearing are incorrect -- they do not.  More often than not (in my experience) all they do is introduce an added amount of latency; double buffering is perfectly fine if you ask me.  In all my years I've yet to see a single DirectX application using exclusively triple buffering that solves screen tearing.  (Note to those who want to debate me about this: you're wasting your time, I will not discuss it.  What I said is true and based on my entire experience in every single regard, including for commercial games, and your efforts debating/argument will be wasted time on your part)<br /><br />Proper Vsync can be accomplished.  Go look at the NES emulator that was just released (mentioned here on the forum) called kindred, it gets windowed mode Vsync correct on OSes like XP SP3 with DX9.  Ask him to describe his buffering + Vsync mechanism and/or provide some example code.  It's supposedly even easier to accomplish on DX10 (Vista onward); guys like James here on the forum has an emulator that does proper Vsync on DX10 and later.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

