					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">By buffering he's referring to either <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_buffering" class="postlink">double buffering or triple buffering</a>.<br /><br />Please note that people who say these techniques solve screen tearing are incorrect -- they do not.  More often than not (in my experience) all they do is introduce an added amount of latency; double buffering is perfectly fine if you ask me.  In all my years I've yet to see a single DirectX application using exclusively triple buffering that solves screen tearing.</div><br />Buffering of course has to be synchronized or else you'll get tearing. Buffering without sync can still be useful if you compose the scene in a roundabout fashion or draw things over others during composition. Triple-buffering is meant to reduce latency by allowing the producer to continuously generate frames, with the video system displaying the &quot;freshest&quot; one.</div>

